The logistic model and its generalizations are useful in the description of growth for many applications, including biology. Phenomenological uses were originally proposed by Richards [18], based on historical discussions by Gompertz [19] and previous work by Von Bertalanffy [20, 21]. Such logistic functions can be viewed as a particular reduction of SIR models to a single variable, i.e. the accumulated population A, which is the time integral of I under the condition \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
